caption: I come here often with my girlfriend and our parents. The foods so delicious and we missed it a lot during quarantine. Our favorite part about this place is the ambiance and the drinks from our bartender Anne. She knows us by name and has learned the style cocktails each of us enjoy individually and drinks are always made to our liking. She also makes excellent recommendations off of the specials menu when we’re unsure of what to order. Highly recommend this place! We are frequent fliers at the TWA hotel and LOVE this place!

The braised lamb shanks were wonderful...I would have liked a wee more vegetable ...just me. Perhaps because it was a Sunday evening, there was very minimal wait staff. Our person was efficient and clearly overworked, being the only server for a large area. Luckily, we were there for friendship and the speed of service worked. This place is welcoming and cozy.  If I am again in the tip of Manhattan, I will get myself to The Paris Cafe.

Located in the  historic seaport district of Manhattan and a  block from the iconic Brooklyn bridge,  the Paris opened in 1873 as a hotel with a bar downstairs. Today it's a  bar/restaurant. The interior has seen renovations with the passage of time; the most recent was after hurricane Sandy, the interior has an inviting  charm. Both the drink and food are top notch.

Back in my old Wall Street days, the Paris Cafe was a 125 year old dive bar which was on the corner of the same block that the old historic Fulton Fish Market stood on.  They had inexpensive drinks & the freshest clams & oysters you could find in NYC!  Boy have times changed, the old Fulton Fish Market has moved to the Bronx, and the Paris Cafe is now a 145 year old upscale establishment.  I was craving clams on the half that day, but alas, no more. The beautiful bar backdrop is I believe, original,  but the place is by far more upscale than is was back in the day!  I did get clams, but in a lemon cream sauce that was very delicious...everyone thoroughly enjoyed their meals!

The food and atmosphere was decent.  However, there were several issues with the staff.  The host was inattentive when we arrived and when we left.  There was not Goodbye and Thank You for your Patronage.  This wasn't because the place was busy but because he was too busy playing with his cell phone.  At one point,. I asked him to bring me a mixed cocktail off the menu and it was evident that he was unfamiliar with it.  One of my cocktails arrived overfilled and was delivered with a soaking wet cocktail napkin.  My dinner plate was delivered facing backwards.  The chef had specifically arranged it with a front/back.  When the check arrived, it was for the incorrect order altogether.  This place seems to be a perfect candidate for one of those restaurant nightmares television shows.  There are aspects that are functioning very well and others that are completely flawed.  I predict that this comes down to a management issue.
